<FIRST>u i AM-Flight103 1stLd-Writethru a0576 04-16 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0576,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Gadhafi, Palestinian Group Planned Pan Am Bombing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with report on Ghadafi, Palestinian
group; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper reported Sunday that the bombing of
Pan Am Flight 103 was conceived during a meeting last year between
Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi, a Palestinian group and Iran's
Revolutionary Guards.
   The Sunday Telegraph attributed its information to U.S.
intelligence sources. The Palestinian group, the Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine-General Command headed by Ahmed Jibril,
has been a prime suspect in the bombing.
   The newspaper said U.S. intelligence officers tracked and
monitored the meeting early last year in Libya, where the
participants discussed the coordination of their operations against
U.S. targets.
   It said Libyan officials in Europe provided logistical support
for the bombing, which was planned and carried out by the
Palestinian group.
   ``U.S. officials believe they now have the names of members of
the terror network,'' the newspaper said. ``The crisis looming
before President Bush is what he does about it.''
   It did not elaborate on the purported participation of the
Revolutionary Guards, the fanatical corps formed by Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini.
   A bomb ripped apart the Boeing 747 over the Scottish town of
Lockerbie on Dec. 21, killing all 259 people aboard the jumbo jet
and 11 on the ground.
   Another British newspaper, the Observer, reported Sunday that
Pan Am has refused to disclose to U.S. investigators details of a
review of its own security carried out by hired consultants two
years ago.
   The weekly said it had obtained sections of the report by the
Israeli security consultants KPI, which it said criticized what it
called Pan Am's ``misguided security concept'' and warned the
airline was ``highly vulnerable to most forms of terrorism.''
   The newspaper said KPI, hired in 1987 at a cost of $460,000,
recommended security improvements on Pan Am airliners. But it said
that according to the U.S. House Subcommittee on Government
Activities and Transportation, the consultants' advice had not been
acted on before Lockerbie.
   The newspaper said the subcommittee's investigation into Pan
Am's failure to act on warnings issued before the disaster has been
severely hampered by the refusal of the airline and the Federal
Aviation Administration to release vital information.
   It said Pan Am has argued that to answer many of the committee's
questions would be ``detrimental'' to its security and would
prejudice its position in litigation with relatives of the victims.
</TEXT>
