<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-89 0051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WinerySlayings 4thLd-Writethru a0583 04-16 0873</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Winery Slayings, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0583,0896</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Find Bodies of Worker's Two Daughters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to CORRECT child's age to 1 sted 2 to reflect
amended hospital records; ADDS quotes from hospital official; picks up
6th graf pvs, ``She made...'; INSERTS 1 graf after 12th, `Friday's attacks...'
to ADD no evidence that daughters were sexually abused; picks up 13th graf
pvs, `Police helicopters...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLEN ELLEN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities searching Saturday for a
winery worker accused of killing his wife and four other people
found the bodies of two of his daughters, and a third was
discovered alive with her throat cut.
   The bodies were found near a landfill transfer station in
California's wine country, not far from where Ramon Salcido, 28,
fled Friday with his daughters, Teresa, 1; Carmina, 3, and Sofia,
4, authorities said.
   ``We do know in fact they are Salcido's children,'' Sonoma
County Sheriff Richard Michaelsen said of the victims.
Investigators could identify the youngsters from photographs, he
said.
   The surviving child was identified as Carmina, authorities said.
She was in stable condition after surgery at Petaluma Valley
Hospital in Petaluma.
   ``It appears her vital signs are stable, and she's going to make
it,'' said Chuck Cowen, a hospital administrator.
   ``She had a cut in her throat that was 5 to 6 inches long, just
above the Adam's apple,'' Cowen said. ``I don't know how deep, but
it was more than superficial.
   ``She was crying when she came in, but was able to make some
sounds,'' he said. The girl suffered damage to her vocal cords but
doctors believe she will recover.
   ``She made indications to investigators that her father cut her
throat and that it occurred sometime last night,'' Sheriff's Lt.
Gary Zanolini said. ``They were apparently dumped over a cliff near
the dump.''
   The three girls were spotted in a ravine near the dump between
Petaluma and Sonoma by a man looking for a tool to pry a camper
shell off a truck, Michaelsen said. The highway patrol was notified
shortly before 3 p.m.
   ``At first he thought they were dolls,'' the sheriff said. The
man, whom he would not identify, went to get a worker from the
dump, and the two found ``yet another horrible scene,'' Michaelsen
said.
   ``I tried to talk to the little girl who was still alive and I
tried to comfort her,'' said Tim Smith, a landfill worker who went
to investigate. ``She tried to speak and she gurgled from her
throat. Her throat was nearly cut from ear to ear.''
   Sheriff's Lt. Chuck Smith said the two slain girls appeared to
have been at the dump ``for some time'' but that it was not known
how they died.
   There was no immediate sign of Salcido, but Smith said
authorities were searching for a brown 1967 Ford station wagon
someone saw near the dump.
   Friday's attacks on Salcido's two sisters-in-law, 8 and 12, in
which both were sexually assaulted and one was nearly decapitated,
had heightened fears for his daughters, who vanished from the house
where his wife was slain. Salcido also allegedly slew his
mother-in-law and a co-worker.
   There was no evidence that Salcido's daughters had been sexually
molested, Michaelsen said.
   Police helicopters searched the pretty wine country north of San
Francisco. Lawmen over most of this 1,000-mile-long state were on
alert for Salcido, whose 10-year-old car was discovered abandoned
20 miles south in San Rafael.
   Investigators received hundreds of calls from people who claimed
to have seen the burly, black-haired Salcido everywhere from Sonoma
County to Los Angeles, 400 miles to the south.
   Authorities on Friday found the battered and slashed bodies of
Salcido's mother-in-law, Marian Louise Richards, 47, and her
children, Marie, 8, and Ruth, 12, inside their blood-splattered
house in Cotati.
   ``It's a butcher shop in there,'' a policeman said after
emerging from the neat, pale yellow home in a well-tended
middle-class neighborhood.
   At the ranch of a prominent grower, Salcido wounded Kenneth
Butti in the shoulder, said Michaelsen. Butti, 33, worked with
Salcido, a forklift operator, at Grand Cru Winery.
   Sheriff's deputies went to the winery, where they found
assistant winemaker Tracey Toovey alongside his car, dead of
gunshot wounds.
   Deputies went to Boyes Hot Springs and found Salcido's wife,
Angela, 24, who apparently had been beaten and stabbed to death,
Michaelsen said.
   Michaelsen said the bloodbath could have been triggered by a
child support case that came to a head last week. Salcido was
ordered to pay $511 a month to his ex-wife, Debra Ann Salcido, and
nearly $6,000 in back payments.
   Ms. Salcido was under police protection Saturday, authorities
said.
   A next-door neighbor said Salcido was fiercely jealous and
habitually drove home from his job during the day to spy on his
wife.
   ``He's crazy, he was always going around with a gun,'' said
Richard Clark. ``I could see it coming.''
   ``One time he threatened to blow (his wife's) head off,'' Clark
said. ``He said if he found someone ... with his wife he'd kill
them. He was real jealous. He drank a lot. Two or three times a day
he would come home from the winery to see if someone was with his
wife.''
</TEXT>
