<FIRST>r i AM-China-Quake     04-16 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Quake,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Rocks Southwest China; 4 Dead, 5 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful earthquake destroyed 30 homes in a
remote village in southwest China early Sunday, and an official
report said at least four people were killed and five injured.
   The exact number of casualties was not known because
communication with some towns in the area was broken, the state-run
Xinhua News Agency said.
   The quake, which measured 6.7 on the Richter scale, struck at
5:34 a.m. near the town of Batang, which is close to Sichuan
province's western border with Tibet, the State Seismological
Bureau said.
   Over the next seven hours, more than 1,000 aftershocks were
recorded, five measuring above 4 on the scale, Xinhua quoted
provincial scientists as saying.
   The affected region of Sichuan is a densely populated rural
mountain region. Many of the residents are Tibetans. Population
figures were not immediately available.
   Xinhua said about 30 houses collapsed in Sangdagou village in
Zhubalong township, the epicenter of the quake. It said cracks
appeared in 80 percent of the houses in nearby Batang.
   A bridge on the Jinsha River, which passes through Batang, was
damaged along with water conservation and power facilities, Xinhua
said.
   Premier Li Peng, who returned to Beijing on Sunday after a
five-day visit to Japan, immediately was briefed on the earthquake
and sent Sichuan officials a message of sympathy, Xinhua said. It
said he urged them to take steps to minimize possible losses from
aftershocks and restore life to normal.
   Xinhua said rescue teams were en route to the epicenter.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. A quake measuring 6 or higher can cause severe damage
in a populated area.
   An earthquake measuring 7.6 killed 730 people and injured about
4,000 in November in Yunnan province, south of Sichuan. It was
China's worst earthquake since the 1976 temblor that leveled most
of the northeastern city of Tangshan.
</TEXT>
