<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-89 1229EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Grandparents-Support     04-16 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grandparents-Support,0745</SECOND>
<HEAD>Case Draws Attention to Wisconsin Grandparent Liability Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSHKOSH, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state law that forces grandparents to
support the children of their sexually active young teen-agers
should not have been applied in the case of a 12-year-old who
fathered a child by a 19-year-old woman, the boy's angry father
says.
   The man, a dairy farmer who is under court order to submit
financial information on his ability to pay support, says the law
is unfair and that the woman should have been held responsible. His
complaints have added fuel to debate over the law, which could be
allowed to expire this year.
   Even a former prosecutor who decided not to press charges
against the woman, because she is slightly retarded, said that now
that she is a legislator she will support changes in the statute.
The decision by prosecutors not to pursue the case prevented the
boy's family from being exempted from the support requirement.
   Wisconsin was one of the first states to pass such a law holding
parents financially responsible for children born to their
children. Since then, several other state have considered the issue
and a few have passed similar laws, said Rep. Marlin Schneider,
chief sponsor of the measure.
   The law is due to expire Dec. 31 under a ``sunset'' provision.
Schneider said he will continue to support it ``until we have
something better,'' but said it might need some refinement in light
of cases like that of the boy.
   ``No one ever thought of the bizarre circumstances like this,''
he said.
   Figures cited by Schneider show that as of last October, 13
grandparents or sets of grandparents across the state had been
ordered to pay support. The average support was $80 per month.
   Last week, a Winnebago County judge ordered the dairy farmer to
submit financial information within 30 days for the court to decide
whether he must pay child support.
   The farmer, who spoke on the condition his name not be used,
said he believes Wisconsin's grandparent liability law is unfair in
his son's case because of the age of the woman.
   ``She was an adult. She should have known better,'' said the
grandfather. His son, now 15, has no contact with the child, born
in August 1987, he said.
   If the woman had been convicted of first-degree sexual assault,
the boy's parents would have become exempt from the child-support
liability, but the case was never prosecuted.
   State Rep. Peg Lautenschlager, who was then a district attorney,
decided against prosecuting the woman. She said she believes she
made the correct decision because the woman was mildly retarded and
functioned at a level significantly lower than her physical age.
The woman was required to receive counseling, she said.
   ``It was a most inappropriate case for prosecution,'' said Ms.
Lautenschlager.
   Milton Schierland, the Winnebago County assistant corporation
counsel who has pursued the case to try to obtain child support
payments on behalf of the state, said he has the baby's best
interests at heart.
   ``We're not bullying a poor set of grandparents,'' he said.
   ``On the surface, I would say this sounds terrible. This sounds
like something the legislation was not designed to do,'' Schierland
said.
   But he said he believed if people knew the underlying facts of
the case, which county officials cannot discuss because the boy is
a minor, ``they would not feel that way at all.''
   Robert Swain, an attorney for the boy's parents, argues that the
boy was not a teen-ager and the grandparent liability law is
directed at the conduct of teen-agers.
   ``Secondly, he is under the age of consent for having sexual
relations,'' Swain said. ``Thirdly, she is an adult. She's the one
who is supposed to be exercising responsibility for her conduct.''
   The case has drawn the attention of the Wisconsin Civil
Liberties Union, which has opposed the grandparent liability law
since it was passed in 1985 as part of a broader Wisconsin act
aimed at preventing teen-age pregnancies.
   Ms. Lautenschlager said she believes the law is based on a
``faulty premise'' that holding the parents of a child who has a
child financially responsible would reduce promiscuity.
   Schneider said the law was never intended to punish anyone but
was meant to urge parents to discuss sexual matters with their
children.
</TEXT>
