<FIRST>r a AM-BridgeCollapse     04-16 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bridge Collapse,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bridge Collapse Kills One, Two Weeks After Eight-Fatality Span Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Department of Transportation
knew of structural problems with a highway bridge well in advance
of the span's collapse in which eight people were killed earlier
this month, records show.
   A second bridge collapse, meanwhile, killed one teen-ager and
injured two others riding with him Saturday night. The pickup
landed upside down on railroad tracks 25 feet below the 40-year-old
wooden bridge near the eastern Tennessee town of Oliver Springs,
according to Trooper Ray Fletcher.
   It was not immediately clear whether the 25-foot section of the
bridge had already collapsed or it crumbled as the truck drove over
it, police said.
   The accident killed Ronald W. Gallaher, 16, of Oliver Springs.
His brother, Derwin, 14, was in stable condition Sunday at the
University of Tennessee Medical Center in Knoxville. Timothy E.
Seiber, 16, of Oliver Springs was in serious condition at Methodist
Medical Center in Oak Ridge.
   Saturday's collapse in eastern Tennessee came exactly two weeks
after the failure of the Hatchie River bridge, 45 miles north of
Memphis in the western part of the state. Eight people died when
the U.S. 51 span gave way, plunging their cars into the flooded
river.
   That accident was thought to have been caused by high water
washing out or ``scouring'' soil away from bridge supports.
Tennessee Department of Transportation records show the
deficiencies were discovered during inspections in 1985 and 1987.
   But bridge inspection reports at the agency's office in
Nashville showed no indication that recommended repairs were made.
   Maintenance reports kept at the department's regional office in
Jackson, Tenn., have been turned over to state Attorney General
Larry Teague, said William Moore Jr., civil engineering director in
Jackson. He declined to comment on the records Friday.
   ``As far as I know, no major maintenance has been done on that
bridge in the last several years,'' he told a Memphis newspaper,
The Commercial Appeal.
   The transportation department will hire an Illinois engineering
company to investigate the Hatchie River collapse, Moore said.
   Inspections in July 1985 and September 1987 showed evidence of
scouring at the Hatchie River bridge and recommended that steps be
taken to protect four bridge supports.
   Those inspection reports should have been warnings of potential
future problems, said P.K. Basu, a civil engineer and professor at
Vanderbilt University's School of Engineering.
   ``If scouring is happening, that's a danger signal right
there,'' Basu said. ``Right away, they should have inspected under
the water. They should have looked at it and fixed it right then.''
   In a news conference after the Hatchie River accident, Tennessee
Transportation Commissioner Jimmy Evans said that after the 1987
inspection, ``We saw nothing that unduly concerned members of the
bridge inspection division.''
   He said the span was visually inspected in February because of
river flooding, but ``we did not see anything that would unduly
concern us about any movements of the bridge at all.''
   Basu said such a visual inspection ``is worthless.''
</TEXT>
