<FIRST>r a AM-ImeldaMarcos     04-16 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Imelda Marcos,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Philippine First Lady Says Problems Mount But She'll Persevere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imelda Marcos, faced with the prospect of
standing trial alone on racketeering charges, describes her life
these days as a ``comic tragedy.'' But she remains optimistic that
``someone will decide what's right and we will go home.''
   In some respects, the former Philippines first lady's problems
would rival the plot of any soap opera: her husband is serious ill;
her children are scattered across the world; her assets are frozen;
loyal employees face deportation; her mother-in-law lies unburied
for nearly a year; she cannot go home.
   ``The problems just overlap, one after another,'' Mrs. Marcos
said in a recent interview. ``But now, Ferdinand is alive. I am not
in jail. So, there is hope.
   She said her and her husband's case ``has become such a
humongous monster that nobody wants to touch it with a 10-foot
pole. But I think someone will decide what's right and we will go
home.''
   Mrs. Marcos said that those who might accuse her of creating her
own problems do not understand her cultural background, her husband
or the country he ruled for 20 years.
   ``I grew up around everything American, American food, American
music ... USA, red, white and blue. The way I learned the song it
was `God Bless the Philippines.' We were your only colony,'' she
said. U.S. rule, which began during the Spanish-American War of
1898, continued until 1946.
   ``We were not just your friends, your allies, we were one in
spirit with America,'' she said. ``To give us justice now is to
show that your system is working throughout the whole world.''
   She disagrees vehemently with the U.S. government's version of
the Marcoses' exile to Hawaii in 1986 and the subsequent charges of
stealing more than $100 million from the Philippine government and
stashing it in the United States.
   Philippine President Corazon Aquino claims they stole billions
from the country's treasury and has banned their return, although
neither Ferdinand nor Imelda has been charged with fraud in their
homeland.
   Marcos, who has been in a hospital since Jan. 15 but recently
was removed from the intensive care unit, has been found by a
doctor to be unable to travel to New York to appear in court.
   A court conference on the case is scheduled for Monday, when a
trial date might be set for Mrs. Marcos. The 59-year-old former
beauty queen says she is certain she'll be vindicated and doesn't
expect to stand trial until after her husband either dies or
recovers.
   ``My duty is to him, that I am by his side when he needs me,''
she said. ``I really believe I'm here because of Marcos. I just
came in for the ride, the marriage ride.''
   Although she says she's no longer upset by critical media
coverage, Mrs. Marcos said she was amazed by those who say she
lives extravagantly.
   Her hillside home overlooks Honolulu and the Pacific Ocean and
she travels in a black limousine. But she also frequents discount
stores and says she often eats Chinese takeout food.
   ``The people below the hill may think it's a mansion, but I came
from a palace,'' she said. ``It's a step down for me. It's a lot
less.''
   Mrs. Marcos said her dream is that her husband will recover, her
family will be reunited, they will all return to the Philippines,
where Marcos' mother, who died last May, ``can finally be laid to
rest.''
   Although her daughter, Irene, and son, Ferdinand Jr., are free
to travel in the United States, another daughter, Imee, is exiled
in Morocco because she refused to testify before a grand jury
investigating her parents.
</TEXT>
