<FIRST>u w AM-Abortion-Breakdown     04-16 0690</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Breakdown,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion Demographics Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a breakdown of the characteristics of
the women who were questioned in an abortion survey by The Alan
Guttmacher Institute, and a comparison of the rates for the various
groups to their proportion among all women aged 15 to 44,
considered to be the primary childbearing ages.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>AGE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Some 33.1 percent of women receiving abortions were aged 20 to
24, nearly double their share of all women between 15 to 44, which
was 17 percent.
   Women aged 25 to 29 constituted 22.3 percent of those seeking
abortions and 18.9 percent of the overall population.
   Those aged 18 and 19 were 13.8 percent of the abortion clients
and 6.2 percent of all women, and women aged 15 to 17 were 10.8
percent of abortion clients and 9.4 percent of all women.
   On the other side of the scale women aged 30 to 34 made up 11.7
percent of those obtaining abortions and 18.4 percent of all women
in the reproductive ages.
   The 35 to 39 age group was 5.7 percent of those seeking
abortions and 16.3 percent of women in general. And women over age
40 were 1.7 percent of the abortion clients and 13.7 percent of all
women.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ETHNICITY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Although Hispanic women made up 8.4 percent of all women, they
accounted for 12.8 percent of those seeking abortions.
   Non-Hispanic women accounted for 87.2 percent of abortion
clients and 91.6 percent of the female population.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>RACE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The percentage of non-white women who had abortions, 31.4
percent, was nearly double their representation in the population
as a whole. White women made up 83.3 percent of the population but
68.6 percent of those seeking abortions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SCHOOL</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Women attending school constituted 31.1 percent of those seeking
abortions, but only 20.5 percent of all women. Those not attending
school were 79.5 percent of women and 68.9 percent of abortion
clients.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MARITAL STATUS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Women who had not been married constituted the bulk of those
seeking abortions, 63.3 percent, while they made up only 35.7
percent of all women aged 15 to 44.
   Divorced women made up 11.2 percent of abortion clients compared
to 8.2 percent of all women. Those who are separated were 6.4
percent of those seeking the procedure and 3.3 percent of women in
general.
   Married women, who constituted 52.1 percent of all women aged 15
to 44, made up 18.5 percent of those who sought abortions.
   Widows were 0.6 percent of abortion clients and 0.7 percent of
the overall female population.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LIVING ARRANGEMENTS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Women who were cohabiting constituted 17.4 percent of abortion
clients although they were only 3.4 percent of all women. Those not
cohabiting were 96.6 percent of all women and 82.6 percent of those
seeking abortions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EMPLOYMENT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Women holding jobs constituted 68.1 percent of abortion clients
and 64.2 of all women in the age group. Those not working were 31.9
percent of those seeking abortions and 35.8 percent of all women.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>INCOME</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The highest rates of abortion were for women with family incomes
between $11,000 and $24,999. That group accounted for 33.8 percent
of all abortions but was only 29.2 percent of all women.
   Women with family incomes under $11,000 recorded 33.1 percent of
abortions although they made up 14.9 percent of all women
   The 55.9 percent of women in families with incomes of $25,000
and up accounted for 33.1 percent of abortions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>RESIDENCE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Women living in metropolitan areas accounted for 85.7 percent of
abortions although they were 77.1 percent of women. Those in
non-metro areas were 22.9 percent of women and 14.3 percent of
those receiving abortions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>RELIGION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Women reporting no religious affiliation outnumbered their share
of the population by the greatest amount _ constituting 22.2
percent of abortions but only 5.5 percent of all women.
   Those reporting themselves as Protestants were 41.9 percent of
the abortion clients and 57.9 percent of all women. Catholics were
32.1 percent of women and 31.5 percent of the abortion clients.
   Jewish women constituted 2.5 percent of all women and 1.4
percent receiving abortions. Those listing their religion as other
were 2.9 percent of abortion clients and 2 percent of all women.
</TEXT>
