<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-MoneyBags     04-16 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Money Bags,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Bag of $758,000 Found in Bamboo Thicket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man gathering bamboo shoots stumbled onto a bag
with $758,000 in cash Sunday in the same thicket where a similar
find was made five days earlier, authorities said.
   Officials still aren't sure how the two bags with identical
amounts of cash ended up in the bamboo thicket 35 feet off a road
in Kawasaki southwest of Tokyo. Police suggested earlier that the
first bag may have come from a crime.
   The second bag turned up about 100 feet from where a restaurant
owner discovered the first one Tuesday, police said.
   Authorities did not identify the man who found the second bag
Sunday. He made the find as he and about 20 other people, including
three family members, looked for bamboo shoots to eat at home,
police said.
   The first bag, made of vinyl, carried damp and rotting bills.
Some of the cash, all in 10,000-yen notes equal to about $76 each,
was bundled with bank tape dated from 1985 to 1986.
   Seie Sato, 39, found the first bag while looking for bamboo
shoots for use at his restaurant and home. Under Japanese law, he
can keep the money if it is not claimed within six months.
   However, Sato told The Associated Press he hopes the owner of
the cash will soon report to police. So many reporters have called
to interview him, Sato said, he hasn't been able to work in his
restaurant.
</TEXT>
