<FIRST>r a AM-TeenStarved     04-16 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Starved,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cottams Plead Innocent In Son's Starving</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WILKES-BARRE, Pa. (AP) _ A couple have pleaded innocent to
third-degree murder charges in the starvation of their teen-age
son, who died after the family refused to buy food with money set
aside for a church tithe.
   Leona and Larry Cottam are charged in the Jan. 3 death of their
son, Eric, 14. They and their daughter, Laura, 12, were
hospitalized for treatment of malnutrition. Laura has since been
placed in a foster home.
   The couple, who have been jailed, unable to make bail, since
their arrest in January, entered their innocent pleas at a hearing
Friday.
   According to police, the Cottam family went largely without food
for six weeks, refusing to spend the only money they had _ more
than $3,500 set aside as a religious tithe.
   The family has been estranged from the Seventh-day Adventists
church since Cottam, 39, was dismissed as a minister because he and
his 38-year-old wife refused to send their two children to
church-run schools.
   Eric and Laura were schooled at home after their parents won a
two-year court battle.
   Officials of the Seventh-day Adventist Church say the religion
does not advocate fasting, holding a tithe instead of buying food
or turning down offers of help.
   One of the Cottams' attorneys, public defender Al Flora Jr.,
said he would seek to have the trial moved to another county or
have jurors picked from another county because of the wide
publicity given the case.
   Attorneys for the couple have argued in pretrial hearings that
the Cottams should not have been charged in their son's death
because he chose not to eat out of his own religious convictions.
   The Cottams must be tried before July 4 or they would be
released on $1 bail under state court rules. Both are jailed in
lieu of $50,000 bail.
   They face a maximum sentence of 20 years in prison if convicted
of third-degree murder.
</TEXT>
