<FIRST>r i AM-Half-TankLaw     04-16 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Half-Tank Law,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanks A Lot: Motorists Can Face Fines For Buying Bargain Gas Across
Border</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beginning Monday, motorists leaving this island
republic with less than half a tank of gas will be breaking the law
and could end up paying a fine of nearly $260.
   The so-called ``half-tank law,'' enacted by Parliament earlier
this month, is designed to stop people from crossing into
neighboring Malaysia to buy gas that is 20 percent cheaper. Premium
gas costs 48 cents a liter in Singapore.
   The bargain-hunting motorists were costing the government more
than $1 million a month in excise taxes, officials claimed.
   A single road across a causeway connects Singapore with the
southern tip of the Malay Peninsula. Signs near the immigration
post portray the fuel gauge of a car and warn, ``Singapore cars
please top up.''
   Disconnecting your fuel guage won't work. A fine of about $2,580
or three months in jail faces Singapore motorists with non-working
fuel gauges.
   ``Customs officers will walk around cars and check fuel gauges
at random while they are clearing immigration formalities,'' said
Lee Yew Kim, director-general of the Customs and Excise Department.
   ``We will do our jobs unobtrusively. Motorists will not even
have to wind down their windows,'' he said.
   Finance Minister Richard Hu said about 6,000
Singapore-registered cars cross into Malaysia daily.
   Opposition member Lee Siew Choh said the measure is
``irrational, schizophrenic and illogical,'' a protectionist move
that could damage relations with Malaysia.
   Malaysian newspapers reported that gas station owners in Johor
Baru, across the causeway from Singapore, could lose more than
$370,000 weekly in gas sales to cars from Singapore.
</TEXT>
