<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     04-16 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DODGEVILLE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bulls jumped a fence and did the old
Casanova love-'em-and-leave-'em routine with a herd of heifers, a
lawsuit going to trial in Iowa County Circuit Court this week
claims.
   A jury will consider the $73,000 lawsuit filed by Michael and
Paul Mieden of Barneveld, who claim two of their neighbor's bulls
jumped a fence and impregnated 32 Meiden heifers during the summer
of 1986.
   The Miedens' suit alleges that neighbor Lloyd Vivian was
negligent because of his ``failure to properly maintain and repair
a fence on the boundary line'' between the two properties.
   The Miedens claim many of the impregnated heifers were so young
that their careers as milk producers were diminished by their early
pregnancies. A heifer is a young cow that has not yet had a calf.
   Colleen Martin, an appraiser hired by the Miedens, said in court
documents that the heifers were bred when they were ``too small to
produce milk efficiently.''
   As a result, the animals ``will never reach full potential in
size and production due to this crisis,'' Ms. Martin said.
   The case was set for a Nov. 28 jury trial, but it was delayed
after one expert witness was taken ill and hospitalized. The trial
was rescheduled for Monday and is expected to last about a week,
said Iowa County Clerk of Courts Carolyn Olson.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Anderson and Tammy Gottas had become so
accustomed to riding a city bus together that they needed one to
get from the church to their wedding reception.
   ``We met on the bus, we talked on the bus, we pretty much dated
on the bus,'' Anderson said.
   And to honor the central place the city bus system had taken in
their life together, the couple, the wedding party and some of the
guests trooped from the church to a bus stop and caught a
Metropolitan Transit Commission bus to the wedding reception
Saturday.
   Anderson, a 34-year-old computer graphics technician, and
Gottas, a 31-year-old customer service representative, didn't
ordinarily take the same bus from suburban Bloomington to downtown
Minneapolis.
   But after they met last year when Anderson was going to work a
bit later than usual, he started making a point of taking that
later bus. They eventually started dating, and began taking the
same evening bus back to Bloomington as well.
   Then, one evening, Anderson decided to surprise her.
   ``I knew 35W was going to be backed up as usual, bumper to
bumper. I waited until it got really backed up. So I got on my
knees. I am saying, `I love you, do you want to marry me?' and she
is grabbing me, pulling me up,'' he said.
   The bus riders applauded.
   ``I can see a series in this,'' Anderson said. ``Love Bus.''
</TEXT>
