<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-89 1426EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CrossBurning     04-16 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cross Burning,0334</SECOND>
<UNK>Judge Rules KKK Cross-Burning Violated Burning Ordinance</UNK>
<DATELINE>JIM THORPE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has upheld the conviction of a Ku
Klux Klan backer of violating a township fire-control ordinance by
allowing a cross to burn on his property, saying that a Klan
cross-burning was not a religious ceremony.
   ``Were we to conclude, on this record, that KKK is a religion
under the First Amendment, we would have to so qualify every group
who came into court with a Bible, a lighted match and a claim to be
a Christian,'' Carbon County Judge John P. Lavelle said in his
ruling last week.
   According to the court, Joseph A. Lower Jr. and his wife leased
their property for $1 to the Invisible Empire Knights of the Ku
Klux Klan for a July 4 rally last summer.
   Before the rally, township Police Chief Richard Gross informed
Lower that an ordinance prohibited fires after dark.
   However, 36 white-sheeted KKK members gathered on Lower's
property for a rally including speeches and marches, and ignited a
large wooden cross, which burned for about half an hour, Lavelle
said.
   District Justice Bruce Appleton of Palmerton convicted Lower on
Aug. 1 and ordered him to pay $325 for a fine and court costs.
Lower appealed to Lavelle.
   Lower admitted he violated the burning ordinance, but tried to
get the citation dismissed by arguing the ceremony was religious in
nature.
   At an appeal hearing Feb. 16, Mark W. Thomas, a state chaplain
with the KKK chapter in Reading, testified the cross-burning
ceremony was a necessary and integral part of the religious rituals
of the Klan. He said the KKK had no ordained ministers but that
everyone was ordained by God to speak the word of God.
   The judge ruled the KKK was not a religion under federal court
rulings. He also found that Lower was not a victim of selective
prosecution by the township because of his membership with the KKK.
</TEXT>
