<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-89 1432EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Budget     04-16 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Cooks Agree: They've Concocted A Lukewarm Appetizer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Administration and congressional leaders
defended themselves Sunday against charges that their deal to cut
the 1990 budget deficit to $99.4 billion was unrealistic and based
on accounting gimmicks.
   ``This was the best that could be done,'' said the chairman of
the Senate Budget Committee, Sen. Jim Sasser, D-Tenn.
   The White House chief of staff, John Sununu, said the agreement
achieved ``a very significant reduction of the deficit.''
   The most prominent critic has been the chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, who refused to
attend the White House ceremony last Friday announcing the deal.
   Bentsen questioned a provision in the agreement which forecast
an additional $5.3 billion in revenues. The source of that money
has not been negotiated, and President Bush has refused to boost
taxes to cut the deficit.
   Critics of the agreement were angered, said Sununu, because
``there is not a big tax package in there.''
   The extra $5.3 billion, he said, would ``come almost entirely
from the increased revenue that comes when you reduce the capital
gains tax, $4.8 billion, a proposal that I think in the past
Senator Bentsen has been in favor of.''
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady and Sununu said the
administration would not agree to raise revenue next year by
increasing the federal tax on gasoline, but they refused to discuss
whether such a tax as possible for 1991.
   Administration and congressional leaders described the agreement
as an 8-year highwater mark in budget cooperation between Democrats
and Republicans.
   ``I think that what this bipartisanship means is that we put
behind us eight years of confrontation and gridlock that occurred
with the Reagan administration and produced absolutely monumental
peacetime deficits for this agreement,'' said Sasser. ``It sets the
stage for some significant budget reductions'' in 1991 and beyond.
   The chairman of the House Budget Committee, Rep. Leon Panetta,
D-Calif., said: ``The alternative to not working together, frankly,
is chaos. Congress would not be able to put together a budget
resolution, and Congress is not going to do anything about tax
increases without the support of the president. That limited our
choices.''
   Panetta described the agreement as a ``first step. There isn't
anybody, either from the White House or from Capitol Hill, that
doesn't believe more has to be done.''
   Panetta predicted that the budget deficit would fall below the
ceiling of $100 billion set by the Gramm-Rudman law, but Sasser
said, ``I think the deficit will be above $99 billion,'' possibly
as high as $110 billion.
   Sasser called the deal ``a minimalist agreement. I would like to
have done much more.''
   Sasser appeared on the ABC-TV interview program, ``This Week
with David Brinkley,'' Sununu and Panetta on CBS-TV's ``Face the
Nation,'' Brady on NBC-TV's ``Meet the Press.''
</TEXT>
