<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Katyn     04-16 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Katyn,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands March To Honor Massacre Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Solidarity supporters marched
in this Baltic port city Sunday to pay homage to Polish army
officers massacred at Katyn in the Soviet Union during World War II.
   Behind a banner with the word ``Katyn'' painted in black, more
than 5,000 marchers carried urns of soil brought from the graves to
a workers' monument in front of the shipyard where Solidarity was
founded.
   The Rev. Henryk Jankowski, an adviser to Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa, celebrated Mass before the march.
   He demanded that ``everything be revealed'' about the massacre.
``We demand this in the name of arranging, finally, normal
relations with our eastern neighbor,'' Jankowski said. ``Nothing
cures better than truth and honesty.''
   Polish officials have long supported the Soviet account that the
more than 4,000 officers were killed in 1941 by the Nazis after the
Germans invaded the Soviet Union. But the government recently
indicated it may change its position to that of most Poles and
Western historians, who say the Soviet secret police carried out
the massacre on the orders of Soviet leader Josef Stalin in April
1940 when the Soviet Union and Nazi Germany were still allied.
   The Polish side of a joint commission studying the massacre and
other historical ``blank spots'' with the Soviets recently
presented what officials call circumstantial evidence of Soviet
responsibility. There has been no conclusion from the Soviet side.
   Jankowski also called for the truth about the fate of 10,000
Polish officers interned at two Soviet camps who disappeared at
about the same time. Presumed dead, their graves have never been
found.
   Officials gave permission for the march in Gdanks, which
dispersed peacefully except for a delegation of about 150
supporters of a Walesa rival who briefly confronted police.
Witnesses reported some stones were thrown at police, but the group
then dispersed and there were no detentions.
</TEXT>
