<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-89 1452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-StadiumScene     04-16 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stadium Scene,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tradition Hinders Change In British Soccer Stadiums</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Stadium Disaster, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY SIDDONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imagine paying about $7 to stand for two hours
inside a metal cage, with bodies pressed against you and swaying to
chants fueled by centuries of tradition and gallons of beer.
   Stage this uncomfortable scene in a damp, dark stadium that was
40 years old when World War II began, and you have an idea of what
it's like to watch a soccer game in England.
   As they tried to piece together what happened in a crush of
bodies that left 94 fans dead, English sports officials looked at
stadiums where their games are played and said Sunday old habits
may have been among the factors that led to the tragedy.
   ``The public determines whether they like a new development or
not,'' said Andy Williamson, spokesman for the Football League,
referring to efforts to end some traditions in English soccer.
``The clubs have come to the conclusion that they do not.''
   The deaths in the opening minutes of Saturday's soccer cup
semifinal between Liverpool and Nottingham Forest came in the
standing-room section known as the terraces. The victims were
crushed against concrete and steel as thousands of late-arriving
fans poured into the already packed area.
   Officials of the the international soccer federation, FIFA, and
the European counterpart, the Union of European Football
Associations, reiterated Sunday that standing-room sections should
be abolished. English officials said it wasn't that easy.
   ``Clubs have tried to change the way fans watch matches by
eliminating terraces and making their stadiums all-seating. But the
public in England demands the right to stand,'' said Jill Smith, an
administrator for the English Football Association.
   Ms. Smith noted that Coventry, one of the nation's biggest
clubs, was the latest to try to eliminate standing-room areas. It
didn't work.
   ``People wound up standing on the seats,'' she said. ``It's a
very traditional thing, a terribly emotive issue.''
   For someone used to the polished newness of professional
stadiums and arenas in the United States, the top sports facilities
in Britain come as a shock.
   The newest stadium among the 20 clubs in Division 1 was built in
1935. At least 10 teams, including Sheffield, have played in their
stadiums since the 1890s.
   Entrance generally is through a turnstile that squeezes a man of
normal height and weight. Concessions are few and lines are long.
There is no pre-game or halftime entertainment, nor even a
scoreboard clock at most fields.
   Seats are jammed together and posts supporting the upper deck
block the view.
   There are no posts in the terraces, but fans there _ having paid
a general admission fee of about $6.80 _ stand on bare concrete
ledges that ascend from the edge of the field to about 10 feet
above ground level. To watch the game, they must peer through a
steel mesh fence.
   These perimeter fences were installed in most Division 1
stadiums earlier this decade to cut down on crowd violence and keep
rowdy fans off the field. The bright blue fences at Sheffield's
Hillsborough Stadium, where Saturday's tragedy occurred, did that
job too well.
   ``Some of the measures we took to combat hooliganism may now
have turned on us,'' said Williamson.
   Hillsborough was built in 1899. It is counted as one of
England's top facilities, however, and Williamson said Sheffield
and many other first-division fields had undergone renovation since
World War II.
   But updating is one thing; tearing down an old field and moving
a club to a modern venue is another, and such changes have not yet
found support.
   ``Sometimes it was lack of money, sometimes the council has not
given approval, but the fans have never gotten behind the new
stadiums,'' Ms. Smith said. ``They have an emotional attachment to
the old ones.''
   Efforts to draw fans to stadiums early, to avoid the type of
last-minute rush that caused Saturday's disaster, also have not
worked, Williamson said.
   ``The public has been seen to be unexcited by any of the
entertainment that might be offered (before the game),'' he said.
   ``They find their own form of entertainment, whether that's
going to a pub or whatever.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
