<FIRST>r i AM-Jordan     04-16 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jordan,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Financially Troubled Jordan Raises Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Sunday announced steep price
increases on items ranging from gasoline to long-distance telephone
calls as part of an economic reconstruction program for the
financially troubled kingdom.
   Under an agreement with the International Monetary Fund
announced Friday, Jordan also plans to slash its budget deficit to
help solve its debt crisis.
   The agreement paves the way for Jordan to seek rescheduling or
refinancing of its $6 billion debt. It has already fallen behind on
some of the $1.2 billion repayments scheduled for this year.
   The price increases, announced by the official Jordan news
agency, do not affect subsidies on bread, milk, rice and other
staples.
   The price of regular gasoline was raised by 25 percent, to 41
cents a liter from 33 cents. A 20-pound bottle of cooking gas will
cost $3.70, up from $3.33.
   The price of imported cigarettes went from $1.20 to $1.57. The
cost of international phone calls and annual telephone rental fees
went up 10 percent.
   The government also raised the tax on alcoholic drinks from 20
percent to 50 percent for imported beverages and to 40 percent for
local beverages.
   Many workers in this country of 3 million people earn between
$185 and $370 a month. Families often have as many as seven to 10
children.
   The increases follow austerity measures imposed last year when
Jordan devalued the dinar by 40 percent and banned imports of many
luxury goods.
   Per capita income for Jordanians reached nearly $2,000 a year in
the early 1980s, but it has since declined to less than $1,200 a
year. That happened because Jordan is a small country that must
import many essential goods, whose local prices rose because as the
value of the dinar declined.
   The country ran into balance of payments problems when Arab aid
and remittances sent home by Jordanians in the Persian Gulf slumped
along with oil prices in the mid-1980s and Jordan continued to
borrow heavily.
   The kingdom, which produces little oil, has blamed its problems
in part on the failure of Arab oil states to pay it the bulk of the
$1 billion yearly they pledged for a decade at a 1978 Arab summit.
</TEXT>
