<FIRST>u i AM-Germany-Derailment 1stLd-Writethru a0631 04-16 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Derailment, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0631,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Train Carrying Explosive Chemicals Derails; More than 1,000 Evacuated</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with chemical tankers removed, evacuees
allowed back home; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROTENBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A train carrying explosive
chemicals derailed near the central rail station of this northern
city and forced the evacuation of more than 1,000 residents Sunday.
   No one was injured in the accident late Saturday, but 22 cars
derailed, including the tankers carrying propylene oxide and
tolylene diisocyanate, poisonous explosive chemicals used in making
dyes and solvents.
   Police said the first attempt to lift three overturned tankers
carrying the chemicals failed because the cars were ``crushed
together like an accordion.''
   A larger crane was brought in and removed the three tankers late
Sunday, police reported.
   Regional government director Gerhard Blume said there appeared
to have been no leaks from the overturned tankers, which are owned
by the Dow Chemical Co. based in Midland, Mich.
   Police said more than 1,000 residents of the area were roused
from their homes and evacuated to City Hall early Sunday because of
the danger of explosions during the sensitive operation to right
the overturned tankers.
   Juergen Erdmann of the federal railroad office said the evacuees
were told they could return home later in the day and the busy
Bremen-Hamburg line was reopened.
   Rotenburg lies along the Wuemme River about 20 miles east of
Bremen and has a population of more than 140,000.
