<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia-Survivors     04-16 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia-Survivors,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors of Khmer Rouge Urge Adoption of Human Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years after the Khmer Rouge's
brutal reign in Cambodia, 1,000 survivors of its labor camps and
torture chambers are urging adoption of human rights treaties in
their nation.
   ``We are aware ... that the international community may go along
with those who want to dump the Khmer Rouge back on to the
Cambodian people,'' said Kassie S. Neou, who survived the Koch Ro
Teh execution center in Battambang province.
   Fears of a Khmer Rouge return heightened after Vietnam announced
it will withdraw its 50,000 troops from Cambodia by Sept. 30.
Vietnam's 1978 invasion ended the communist group's nearly
four-year attempt to turn Cambodia into a primitive communal
agriculture society.
   The survivors, living in exile, sent the appeal letter, dated
Monday, to Hun Sen, premier of the Vietnamese-installed government
in Cambodia, and to guerrilla leaders opposing him: Prince Norodom
Sihanouk and Son Sann of the Khmer People's National Liberation
Front.
   The Cambodian adversaries have engaged in unprecedented peace
negotiations in the past year and Sihanouk and Hun Sen are to meet
again next month in Indonesia.
   No letter was sent to the Khmer Rouge, the third partner in the
guerrilla coalition and blamed in the death of more than 2 million
of the 8 million population during their 1974-79 rule.
   The appeal was spearheaded by Dith Pran, a New York Times
photographer whose escape to Thailand was depicted in the 1984
movie ``The Killing Fields'' and Haing S. Ngor, the Academy
Award-winning actor who portrayed him.
   ``Fourteen years ago today, Cambodia entered the darkest period
of our 2,000-year history,'' said the letter. ``We are not yet free
from the memory, the loss and the tragic chain of events that has
befallen Cambodia since April 17, 1975.''
   On that day, victorious over the U.S.-backed Lon Nol government,
the Khmer Rouge entered the capital of Phnom Penh, executed
opponents and drove the city's residents, including bedridden
hospital patients, to the countryside.
   The letter asked the Cambodian leaders to abide by the
International Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the
Crime of Genocide, the International Human Rights Convenants and
other internationally approved declarations.
   It asked all parties to facilitate human rights monitoring and
education by Cambodian and international agencies after the
Vietnamese withdraw.
   ``Our hopes for peace are tinged with fear because we do not
believe the tiger has changed its stripes,'' said the letter, which
noted that the Khmer Rouge recently forcibly relocated refugees in
its camps in Thailand.
   There have been reports that the Khmer Rouge has hidden arms
caches for an all-out offensive after the Vietnamese pullout.
   The survivors urged the international community to bring the
Khmer Rouge atrocities before the International Court of Justice at
the Hague.
   The U.N. General Assembly in November added to its annual
resolution on Cambodia an unprecedented condemnation of the
policies of the Khmer Rouge era. The U.S. Congress also adopted an
anti-Khmer Rouge resolution, signed into law in October.
</TEXT>
