<DOCNO> AP890416-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-89 1542EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Ethics 1stLd-Writethru a0664 04-16 0744</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Ethics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0664,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs last graf to CORRECT to 1870's, One of ... corrupt practices</HEAD>
<HEAD>Modern Congressmen Face Tougher Ethical Standards than in Yesteryear</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Wright Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W.DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Daniel Webster would not have understood the
Jim Wright affair.
   When Webster was in the Senate, 1828-50, a fellow lawmaker
charged that he was ``bound hand and foot'' to wealthy backers who
had come up with a fund to support his extravagant life style.
   What, asked Rep. William Yancey of Alabama, was the
Massachusetts senator being paid for?
   Webster, although he had accepted such a fund, didn't bother to
answer.
   Things have changed between the 1840's and the 1980's.
   House Speaker Wright, a Texas Democrat expected to be formally
charged by the House ethics committee Monday with several dozen
rules violations including accepting free use of a condominium and
car from a Texas businessman, has asked for a chance to answer as
soon as possible.
   ``Webster gave no indication ... of being embarrassed when the
matter (of the fund) came up in Congress,'' biographer Irving H.
Bartlett has written. ``That the public might interpret such a
transaction as evidence of the corruption of an elected
representative of the people seems not to have occurred to him.''
   Since Webster's day, however, members of Congress periodically
have been investigated for accepting financial or sexual favors and
for other misdeeds.
   Four representatives and 15 senators have been expelled in the
200-year history of Congress, beginning in 1797 when Sen. William
Blount of Tennessee was accused of conspiring with the British and
the Indian tribes to conquer West Florida.
   The most recent member to be expelled, and the first in 126
years, was Rep. Michael Myers, a Pennsylvania Democrat convicted in
the Abscam bribery scandal, in 1980.
   Last year, Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., convicted in the Wedtech
scandal, resigned after the House scheduled a vote on an ethics
committee recommendation to expel him.
   Censure, the stiffest punishment short of expulsion, has been
voted for seven senators, including Wisconsin Republican Joseph
McCarthy in 1954 and Sen. Thomas J. Dodd, D-Conn., in 1967.
McCarthy was censured for actions ``contrary to senatorial
traditions'' in his investigations of alleged communism and Dodd on
financial grounds.
   It is more than a slap on the wrist.
   ``I think it must be hard for anyone who has not served in the
Senate of the United States to comprehend how devastating censure
can be to a senator,'' Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., the former
Senate majority leader, has said. ``Censure does not remove a
member's right to vote or speak or serve on committees. But, in as
collegial a body as this, censure is an awesome punishment, and,
from all accounts, Senator McCarthy suffered mightily as a result.''
   Twenty-three members have been censured by the House, most
recently Reps. Daniel B. Crane, R-Ill., and Gerry E. Studds,
D-Mass., in 1983 for sexual misconduct with congressional pages.
Crane was defeated for re-election the next year, but Studds is
still in Congress.
   The mildest form of punishment, a reprimand, was instituted in
1975 and has been meted out to a half dozen members of the House.
The most recent was Rep. Austin Murphy, a five-term Pennyslvania
Democrat, rebuked in 1987 for having someone else cast votes for
him on the House floor. Murphy was re-elected last year.
   Rep. George V. Hansen, R-Idaho, was reprimanded in 1984 after
being convicted by a federal court jury of filing false financial
disclosure forms. He was defeated for re-election after his
conviction but before going to prison, where he served just over a
year.
   One of the most sensational cases in recent years involved Rep.
Wayne L. Hays, D-Ohio, who admitted a ``personal relationship''
with staff member Elizabeth Ray but denied hiring her to be his
mistress. Hays resigned in 1976 after the ethics panel voted to
hold public hearings on his case.
   Although the House ethics committee was formed in 1969, it did
not conduct a formal investigation until 1976, when it reprimanded
Rep. Robert Sikes of Florida for a conflict of interest.
   Even before the committee and its procedures, however, the House
was disciplining its members.
   One of the first big scandals came in the 1870's, when Rep.
Oakes Ames of Massachusetts was censured for accepting shares of
stock at bargain prices from Credit Mobilier, a construction
company seeking to obtain favors and block an investigation of its
corrupt practices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
