<HEAD>Refugee Boat Intercepted; Coast Guard Steps Up Patrols Near Haiti</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Coast Guard cutter was sailing to Haiti on Sunday
to return 137 would-be refugees picked up in the Windward Passage
off Cuba, where a record flow of boats is trying to reach Florida
from Haiti, a spokesman said.
   A second cutter has been assigned to double the U.S. patrol in
the waters between Cuba and the Bahamas and airplane surveillance
also has been increased, Coast Guard spokesman Jeff Karonis said.
   ``There are so many boats coming near our shores we decided it
was best to try to block them nearer the source,'' said Karonis.
   Refugees coming within three miles of the U.S. shore must be
given a full hearing to determine whether they are eligible for
admission as refugees fleeing political persecution.
   The Coast Guard has intercepted nearly 2,200 Haitians at sea
this year.
