<HEAD>House To Vote This Week On Base-Closings Package</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: ``The federal...'' to CORRECT to $25
billion sted million; picks up 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``In House...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House decides this week whether to accept
or reject a federal commission's recommendations to shut down 86
military installations and partly close five more.
   A vote on a resolution to disapprove the report of the
Commission on Base Realignment and Closure is scheduled for
Tuesday, and the full House is expected to follow the lead of its
Armed Services Committee. The panel voted 43-4 last month to
support the commission's report.
   Savings from the plan, which also includes substantial changes
at 54 other facilities, were estimated at $694 million a year
initially and $5.6 billion over 20 years.
   The Senate, meanwhile, takes up President Bush's $90 billion
plan to bail out and reform the savings and loan industry, with
Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, promising to
resolve the issue by week's end.
   The federal S&amp;L insurance fund is now more than $25 billion in
debt because of bad loans and, in some cases, fraudulent lending
and accounting practices using government-insured deposits.
   In House debate last week over base closings, representatives
from New Jersey, Illinois and California pleaded with their
colleagues to pass the disapproval resolution, claiming the
commission's report was ``tragically flawed.''
   Rep. Jim Courter, R-N.J., who is opposed to the recommendation
to close New Jersey's Fort Dix, said the data used by the panel was
based on ``incorrect information and clerical error.''
   Rep. Ed Madigan, R-Ill., said no member of the commission
visited Chanute Air Force Base in his state and charged that
closing the facility ``will not achieve the alleged cost savings.''
   But according to law, the commission's recommendations must be
accepted in their entirety. If the resolution of disapproval fails,
the plan will go into effect next month, with base closings to
begin in 1990.
   Rep. Pat Schroeder, D-Colo., a member of the House Armed
Services Committee, said, ``I hear the pain of many members whose
bases will be closed in their districts,'' but reminded her
colleagues that the House voted for legislation creating the
commission.
   The Senate is continuing to hold hearings on the issue.
   The S&amp;L bailout plan is gaining momentum in Congress after
surviving its biggest challenge as Democrats agreed last week to
Bush's financing plan, which is designed to keep the $50 billion
taxpayer cost from showing up in the federal deficit.
   While the Senate considers the bill, the House Banking Committee
also takes up the measure. Tougher capital and regulatory
requirements that Bush backed but were lost in subcommittee action
may be reinstated.
   ``By the time it's all over, he (Bush) may get 90 to 95 percent
of what he wants,'' said Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., a
subcommittee member.
</TEXT>
