<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-16 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Much Colder Air Enters The Northern High Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Colder air mixed with snow pushed onto the northern Plains on
Sunday, and an area of widespread rain along the northern East
Coast gradually moved out to sea.
   The cold air followed a frontal system across Manitoba and
Saskatchewan into the northern Plains. Temperatures fell into the
20s and 30s over the northern Rockies.
   Snowshowers developed east of the Rockies from northern Montana
into western North Dakota. Ahead of the front, rain developed
across southern parts of Montana into parts of the northern Plains.
   A second cold front extended across the upper Great Lakes into
the middle Missouri Valley, and scattered showers broke out ahead
of it over eastern Iowa and northwestern Illinois.
   Low pressure over the Atlantic Ocean south of Cape Cod produced
widespread rain across northern and central New England into parts
of the mid-Atlantic coast. By late afternoon, rain had stopped
falling at New York City as the low moved farther out to sea.
   One to two inches of rain was reported in 24 hours over parts of
New England. Providence, R.I., got an even 2 inches, New York
City's LaGuardia airport got 1.15 inches, and Portland, Maine, had
nearly an inch of rain.
   Temperatures rose into the 90s across the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 20
degrees at Cut Bank, Mont., to 93 at Lubbock, Texas. Sunday's low
for the 48 contiguous states was 22 at Cut Bank, occurring just
before noon.
   For Monday, widespread showers and scattered thunderstorms were
forecast from the central and eastern Great Lakes through the Ohio
Valley into the middle Mississippi Valley. Scattered showers and
thunderstorms also were forecast across extreme southern Florida.
   Highs in the 30s and 40s were predicted from the northern Plains
into the upper Great Lakes; in the 50s from the northern Rockies
through the middle Missouri Valley into the lower Great Lakes, and
across northern New England; in the 80s from the central California
valleys through the southern Rockies and lower Mississippi Valley
into Florida; in the 90s across the desert Southwest; and in the
60s or 70s across much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
