<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-89 1729EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Crack-Strokes     04-16 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crack-Strokes,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Finds Cocaine Abuse Leads To Increased Risk Of Stroke</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocaine abusers, especially those who use the
drug's purer ``crack'' form, are more likely than others to suffer
strokes or cerebral hemorrhages, researchers said Sunday.
   Dr. Patti Peterson, chief of neurology at Detroit Receiving
Hospital, said a three-year study found that 3 percent of cocaine
abusers admitted to the hospital suffered strokes or hemorrhages,
the rupture or clogging of a blood vessel in the brain.
   Most of the abusers were young adults, with an average age of
35, she said.
   ``I don't think the coke abusers know what they're getting
into,'' Ms. Peterson said. ``Three out of a hundred _ I don't like
those odds.''
   She said the abusers had a ``much higher'' rate of strokes than
others. ``There's no way that 3 percent of the 35-year-olds who are
admitted to the hospital have strokes,'' she said.
   The rate of stroke in the general population of similar age is
about 0.05 percent, she said.
   Ms. Peterson and Dr. Patricia Moore, a neurologist at the
hospital, presented their conclusions at the annual meeting of the
American Academy of Neurology.
   From July 1985 to June 1988, they studied 979 cocaine abusers
admitted to the hospital for various reasons. Of those patients, 33
suffered strokes or cerebral hemorrhages. Six of those 33 patients
died and only 17 recovered well enough to be sent home. The others
remain in long-term care, Ms. Peterson said.
   Cocaine increases a patient's blood pressure, which Ms. Peterson
said probably causes the strokes. And with the arrival of the
stronger crack form of cocaine, the problem has gotten worse.
   Crack ``is a purer compound and gets into the bloodstream in
much higher quantities much faster,'' she said.
   ``I think we're going to see a heck of a lot more of this and
it's something we need to look at,'' she said. ``Most people don't
think cocaine when they see people coming in with a stroke.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
