<FIRST>r i AM-China-Students     04-16 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Students,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Demand Rehabilitation of Late Party Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students put up posters at universities Sunday
demanding that Communist officials clear the name of Hu Yaobang, a
reformer who died two years after he was ejected as party chief.
   It was the first large-scale expression of campus discontent
with the government since the winter of 1986-87, when students
marched for democracy in protests that led to Hu's expulsion.
   The 73-year-old Hu died Saturday. He had suffered a heart attack
a week earlier during a meeting of the Politburo, the ruling body
that forced him out as party general secretary two years before. He
remained a Politburo member.
   Hu resigned after charges he failed to put down the nationwide
student marches. Hu was also accused of promoting dangerously high
growth rates through market-oriented reforms and pushing too hard
for Westernization.
   Dozens of posters went up Saturday and Sunday at Beijing
University, the country's leading institution, and at Qinghua and
the People's universities. Students also placed several wreaths at
a monument to China's revolutionary martyrs in central Beijing's
Tiananmen Square.
   The posters praised Hu, obliquely criticized his opponents, and
called for his remains to lie in the mausoleum of legendary leader
and revolutionary hero Mao Tse-tung.
   ``Sincere men have died while hypocrites live on,'' declared one
poster without naming any official. ``Is there any hope left for
our country?''
   Several students at Beijing University and the People's
University said the aim of praising Hu was actually to criticize
those who helped expel him, including conservative party elders and
even senior leader Deng Xiaoping. Deng originally promoted Hu to
party chief but reportedly felt irritated afterward by Hu's
outspokenness.
   At Beijing University, security guards checked identification
papers of everyone entering campus and turned away students from
other schools in an apparent effort to prevent protests. However,
authorities left the posters up.
   Officials are especially intent on maintaining calm on campuses
in the weeks leading up to May 4, the anniversary of the day in
1919 when Beijing University's students began a campaign for
democratic reform in China.
   The campaign, which became known as the May Fourth Movement, was
a training ground for an entire generation of intellectuals,
including many famous writers, politicians and Marxist
revolutionaries.
   Beijing University students who gathered Sunday to mourn Hu
complained that China had made little progress toward reform since
1919.
   ``There is still no individual freedom,'' said one student,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   However, some students looked tense when asked if they would
again take to the streets to demand democracy. ``Maybe we can gain
democracy without marches,'' one said.
   Hundreds crowded around the posted sheets of pink, blue and
white paper covered with huge black characters demanding Hu's
rehabilitation.
   One poster signed by 18 people called for a ``public
clarification'' of Hu's forced resignation, a popular reevaluation
of his ``historical achievements,'' permission for activities to
mourn him, and placement of his remains in Mao's mausoleum.
   Many other students later added their signatures to show support.
   Another poster urged students to ``turn their grief to strength
and carry out democratization to the end.''
   A university lecturer watched the students and said on condition
of anonymity, ``This is good; it reflects what is in people's
hearts.''
</TEXT>
