<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     04-16 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tass Says Afghans Discover Evidence of Guerrilla Massacre</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tass news agency said Sunday that guerrillas
in Afghanistan shot civilians, including children, fleeing the
besieged city of Jalalabad.
   There was no independent confirmation of the report.
   Tass, quoting people it said were witnesses, said victims were
in a convoy of refugees from the city. It said the number of dead
and date of the alleged massacre were unknown.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, called the purported
attack a crime by opponents of Afghanistan's communist government
``akin to those perpetrated by the American military in Vietnam
against the peaceful Vietnamese population.''
   Tass said the convoy was carrying dozens of elderly people,
women and children from Jalalabad toward Kabul when the buses and
trucks were stopped by guerrillas. The anti-communist rebels
reportedly lined up the drivers, shot them, then set fire to the
vehicles, Tass said.
   ``Little children were seized and lifted by the hair; they were
shot and thrown into the Kabul River,'' Tass said. ``Pretty women
were led into the mountains, the rest were killed on the spot.''
   Tass said Afghan government troops discovered the burned buses
and trucks when they reopened the Jalalabad-Kabul highway, which
for two weeks was blocked by Moslem rebels.
   Blockades have been the guerrillas' primary tactic in their
fight to overthrow Afghanistan's communist government, which seized
power in a 1978 coup.
   On Feb. 15, the Soviet Union pulled the last of its troops out
of Afghanistan. Shortly thereafter, guerrillas set up a
government-in-exile in Pakistan and launched their attack on
Jalalabad, 70 miles from the capital.
