<FIRST>r a AM-AirplaneSafety     04-16 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airplane Safety,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Overview Of Jetliners Flawed, Says Newspaper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration's system of
tracking malfunctions on commercial airliners is inconsistent and
rarely accomplishes its goal of predicting and preventing
accidents, a newspaper reported Sunday.
   The report in The Seattle Times included analysis of more than
24,000 ``Service Difficulty Reports'' filed by U.S. passenger and
freight air carriers operating large jetliners during the past two
years.
   The newspaper found drastic inconsistencies in the reporting of
aircraft malfunctions and defects by the 17 largest passenger
airlines under an FAA program. The program's purpose is to
``promote aviation safety through analysis and detection of
mechanical reliability problems.''
   A Service Difficulty Report is a one-page document the FAA
requires airlines to file whenever an aircraft experiences
problems, ranging from cracks found during inspections to engine
shutdowns during flight.
   The FAA acknowledges problems with the SDR program and is
gearing up to overhaul it later this year.
   ``You're into a part of our data that, before you even started
analyzing it, somebody like me would've told you, `Don't spend a
lot of time with it because it's incomplete, inconsistent from
airline to airline, we have non-uniform reporting, we need to
review the items that are required to be reported, we have
timeliness problems,' and on and on and on,'' said Anthony
Broderick, the FAA's associate administrator for regulation and
certification.
   The FAA does not consider the service report system ``a critical
safety data base,'' Broderick said, but aviation experts say SDRs
can and should be an integral part of a warning system for
detecting and fixing airplane defects.
   Industry observers also say if the program were not so
haphazard, it might have prevented a corroded chunk of an Aloha 737
fuselage from ripping away in flight a year ago, or an apparently
mislatched cargo door from tearing a hole in the side of a United
747 two months ago. One person died in the Aloha Airlines mishap
and nine died in the United accident.
   ``There was information held by certain people within the
industry that could have prevented both of those accidents if the
information had been acted on properly beforehand instead of
afterward,'' said John O'Brien, engineering and safety director for
the Air Line Pilots Association.
   Lawmakers, passengers and industry experts, including the Air
Line Pilots Association, have been questioning the reliability of
the system that is supposed to make U.S. air travel safe.
   ``The way it stands now, there's absolutely no uniform
enforcement of criteria used to monitor these airplanes,'' said Dan
Labriola, a Seattle pilot, aeronautical engineer and aviation
consultant.
   One example of the lack of uniformity is that of the more than
24,000 reports checked by the newspaper, nearly 1,700 failed to
include the name of the airline submitting the report.
   In addition, dozens of reports omitted vital information, such
as what caused a malfunction or what the airline did to fix a
defect.
   The Times also reported that airlines have a great deal of
discretion in deciding when to file SDRs. Atlanta-based Delta
Airlines, for example, filed an average of 1.6 reports for each of
its 372 jets over the past two years, and St. Paul-based Northwest
Airlines, with 314 jets and comparable operations, filed 9.6
reports per jet in the same period.
   ``We do know that some airlines are more generous than others in
submitting things to us,'' said FAA spokeswoman Bobbie Mardis. ``We
do know that there are discrepancies.''
   The Air Line Pilots Association would like to see a
comprehensive SDR system put in place with consistent, detailed
reporting by the airlines made mandatory, O'Brien said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
