<FIRST>r a AM-WashingtonBicentennial     04-16 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Washington Bicentennial,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carriage Breaks Down As George Washington's Re-enacted Journey Begins</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT VERNON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,000 people turned out Sunday to
launch a re-enactment of George Washington's carriage trip to his
inauguration, but the actor who played the nation's first president
was forced to leave by van.
   A sparkling antique carriage carrying the modern-day Washington
was less than 100 feet into the 250-mile trek from Mount Vernon to
New York City when it broke down. One of the wheels hit a fence
post and broke the main shaft connecting the harnesses and the
carriage.
   The shaky departure was the only hitch in opening festivities
celebrating the bicentennial of Washington's inauguration on April
30, 1789. The eight-day, 55-event trip will take the Washington
entourage to New York on April 23. A reenactment of the inaugural
ceremony is scheduled for April 30.
   Because of the tight schedule, Washington, played by actor
William Sommerfield, traveled the first five miles in the van
before switching to a back-up carriage that was hauled to a park
along the route.
   The Philadelphia actor stayed in character and was unperturbed.
   ``Strange vehicle, strange vehicle,'' Washington said of his
first automobile ride. ``In the war, the unexpected was the
expected.''
   Also speaking at the ceremony were former Chief Justice Warren
E. Burger, chairman of the Constitution Bicentennial Commission,
and Postmaster General Anthony M. Frank, who dedicated a new
25-cent stamp honoring Washington and the 200th anniversary of the
government's executive branch.
   Among the spectators were some who claimed to be Washington's
descendants. ``This is something very special for me,'' said
Josephine Thomas, 67, of Gulfstream, Fla.
   Sommerfield said he has spent 10 years studying Washington. At
age 58, he is a year older than Washington was when he made the
inaugural journey.
   The actor said he tries to show Washington's little-known
private side.
   ``He had both a private face and a public face,'' Sommerfield
said. ``And his private face was warm and human. He loved the
theater and would go two or three times a week. People said they
loved to sit by him because he had such a hearty laugh.''
   The first leg of the trip took Washington and two companions to
Alexandria. The trip this week will take them through the District
of Columbia, Maryland, Delaware, Pennsylvania, New Jersey and into
New York City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
