<FIRST>r i AM-Libya-PanAm     04-16 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Libya-Pan Am,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libya Denounces Report of Involvement in Pan Am Bombing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya on Sunday angrily denied a report in a British
newspaper linking it to the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103.
   London's Sunday Telegraph, in a report attributed to U.S.
intelligence sources, said the bombing was conceived during a
meeting last year between Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi, a
radical Palestinian group and Iran's Revolutionary Guards.
   Libya's official JANA news agency, in a dispatch monitored in
Rome, said Libya ``has reaffirmed repeatedly its condemnation of
terrorism in general and the disaster suffered by the Pan Am jumbo
jet in particular, and the report published by this newspaper
amounts to no more than a part of the campaign of distortion and
twisting of facts conducted by Zionist and imperialist circles
hostile to Great Jamahiriya (Libya).''
   The Sunday Telegraph said the Palestinian group that
participated in the alleged meeting was the Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine-General Command. The group, headed by Ahmed
Jibril, has been a prime suspect in the bombing.
   Flight 103 exploded over Lockerbie, Scotland on Dec. 21, killing
270 people.
   The Sunday Telegraph said U.S. intelligence officers monitored
the meeting early last year in Libya and the participants discussed
the coordination of operations against U.S. targets.
   It said Libyan officials in Europe provided logistical support
for the bombing, which was planned and carried out by the
Palestinian group.
   It did not elaborate on the alleged participation of the
Revolutionary Guards, created by Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini.
