<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     04-16 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Rejects Military Accusation of Bias</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic church on
Sunday rejected accusations by the armed forces that its human
rights office is smearing the military and the right-wing party
that won elections last month.
   Reading from a church statement, Monsignor Gregorio Rosa Chavez
asked the armed forces ``to permit us to know the evidence behind
this reckless statement.''
   Last week the armed forces press office issued a communique
accusing the church's human rights office, Tutela Legal, of
sponsoring a smear campaign against the military and the rightist
Republican Nationalist Alliance, known as Arena.
   Rosa Chavea told worshipers at the Metropolitan Cathedral that
Tutela Legal ``operates only according to church criteria in its
labor of promoting and defending human rights _ criteria that are
invariable no matter what party is in the government.''
   Arena defeated the incumbent Christian Democrats in March 19
elections and President-elect Alfredo Cristiani is to take office
June 1.
   Arena's founder, retired army Maj. Roberto D'Aubuisson, has been
accused of having links with right-wing death squads that killed
hundreds of suspected leftists in the early 1980s. He has
repeatedly denied the allegations.
   Rosa Chavez, the auxiliary bishop of San Salvador, also
denounced attacks by left-wing guerrillas and security forces last
week in which he said 18 civilians were killed.
   He specifically criticized attacks on businesses by guerrillas
of the Faribundo Marti National Liberation Front, calling them ``as
condemnable as they are traditional.''
   According to both guerrilla and government reports rebels
attacked at least five factories, two shops, 12 bank offices and
two coffee processing plants over the past two weeks.
   Speaking with reporters after the church service, Rosa Chavez
blamed both the guerrillas and government forces for the civilian
deaths.
   Violence ``comes from all sides and it must be fought on all
sides,'' he said. ``The panorama is becoming rough, and for this
the new government will have a difficult task.''
   More than 70,000 people have been killed in the 9-year-old war
between the rebels and U.S.-supported government. Most of the
victims were civilians.
</TEXT>
