<FIRST>r a AM-SawdustFire     04-16 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sawdust Fire,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slow-Burning Sawdust Fire Still Going After Two Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORAM, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People here are fed up with a fire that's
been smoldering in a pile of sawdust bigger than a football field _
after all, it hasn't stopped for two years.
   State fire investigator Jim Wallace said the state may have to
go to court to get the owner of the pile, Desert Mountain Forest
Products, to put out the blaze.
   ``You can negotiate and be a nice guy only so long,'' Wallace
said recently.``If it takes swearing out a warrant, we will.''
   When the wind blows, the hidden fire spouts sparks and smoke
like a volcano, neighbors say.
   Desert Mountain, which makes posts and sticks for California
vineyards, has accumulated a pile 100 yards long, 30 to 50 yards
wide and two stories high in places. The company lies just south of
Glacier National Park.
   Wallace said he suspects spontaneous combustion as the cause of
the fire, but the company's owners blame lightning.
   A similar blaze at a nearby mill wasn't extinguished until the
sawdust pile was bulldozed and clumps of burning material were
blasted apart with fire hoses, Wallace said.
