<FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-89 2100EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GalleryFire     04-16 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gallery Fire,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gallery Owners Assess Losses To Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspicious fire gutted a 104-year-old building
that housed several art galleries, destroying works valued at up to
$50 million, authorities said.
   The spectacular blaze Saturday left the six-story, block-square
building in ruins, with only a few walls standing.
   ``Oh my God,'' cried Roberta Lieberman, part-owner of one of the
eight galleries consumed in the blaze, when she saw the
destruction. ``It's devastating.''
   William van Straaten, whose van Straaten Gallery was among those
destroyed, estimated the combined loss at $50 million.
   Battalion Chief Harold Corrigan said the blaze began in four
sections of the building, leading fire officials to suspect arson.
Flames were seen coming from opposite sides of the structure, and
construction workers who fled the building reported fire on the
upper stories and in the basement.
   Fire Department spokesman Tom Sheppard blamed the severity of
the blaze on contractors who disconnected systems designed to bring
firefighting water into the building. He noted that firefighters
were called to the building on Thursday for a fire that took an
hour to put out.
   ``This wouldn't have happened if they hadn't cut corners,' he
said. ``It's so foolish, now they have nothing.''
   A sprinkler system in the building did not work and fire doors
were open in the building, which was being rehabilitated by the
owners, Mesirow Realty Management Inc., into a mixture of
residential lofts, galleries and shops, officials said.
   Gerald Levin, president of the real estate division of Mesirow,
said Saturday the contractor had done good work on the building.
   ``My understanding was that there (were hookups for) water in
the building,'' Levin said. ``Our design has been at every stage
approved and inspected by the ... Fire Department.''
   The fire occurred one day after a Cook County Circuit judge
refused van Straaten's request to halt construction in the building
because of an alleged fire hazard.
   Circuit Judge David Shields said he issued an order prohibiting
work around van Straaten's gallery but allowing work in the rest of
the building.
   ``The fact that there were incidents in the past didn't lead me
to conclude that there were going to be incidents in the future,''
Shields said.
   The fire ``couldn't have come at a worse time for those
dealers,'' said Leslie Hindman, owner of a gallery four blocks from
the building.
   She said dealers were preparing for Art Expo, an annual spring
event at Chicago's Navy Pier.``For a lot of galleries, that is
tantamount to the Christmas shopping season,'' Ms. Hindman said.
   ``It's one of the most important art fairs in the world and most
of those dealers do a good part of their business during the show.''
   The building, erected in 1885, became the linchpin of the
burgeoning art scene in the city's River North area in recent years.
   The eight galleries dealt mostly with modern American artists,
and buyers from around the world came to buy works, officials said.
</TEXT>
