<FIRST>r a AM-WinerySlayings-Reax     04-16 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Winery Slayings-Reax,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accused Killer Portrayed as Too Possessive of Wife</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Winery Slayings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A winery worker accused of brutally
murdering seven people, including his wife and two daughters, was
depicted by those who knew him as a simple, smiling man who adored
his wife _ too much.
   ``He never caused any problems for anybody,'' said Warren
Brunhagen, a regular at McNeilly's bar in Boyes Hot Springs, where
winery worker Ramon Salcido, 28, was a regular customer.
   Authorities on Sunday continued the nationwide hunt for Salcido
that began Friday when authorities discovered the bodies of his
24-year-old wife, Angela, at their Boyes Hot Springs home; his
mother-in-law and her two young daughters at their home in Cotati;
and a co-worker at the Grand Cru Winery.
   Salcido's three daughters were found with their throats cut
Saturday at a dump between Petaluma and Sonoma. One lived, and was
recovering at Petaluma Valley Hospital on Sunday.
   Salcido, a Mexican native, behaved well and smiled often, but
was ``overly possessive'' of his wife, said John McNeilly, owner of
the tavern about 15 miles from where Salcido worked.
   ``What I saw was not jealousy,'' he recalled. ``He always had
his hands on her and he'd never leave her by herself.''
   Richard Clark, Salcido's next-door neighbor and friend, has said
Salcido was intensely jealous, and often drove home several times a
day to spy on her.
   Clark said he once heard Mrs. Salcido, an aspiring model, cry
out, ``Living with you is like living in jail. You won't let me go
out.''
   The couple recently began arguing loudly, Clark said.
   `I could hear them yelling. ... I guess I knew (the murders)
were coming,'' he said. ``I heard him say, `I'm going to blow your
head off.'''
   Mrs. Salcido's modeling career was just beginning to take off,
Clark said.
   Salcido ``was really jealous,'' the neighbor said. ``Anybody who
was higher up than him or if he had a nicer car than he did _ he
didn't like that. He wanted to be No. 1.''
   Salcido also was upset recently because he was served papers
ordering him to pay nearly $6,000 dollars in overdue child support
and make monthly payments of $511 for a 4-year-old daughter in
Fresno, Clark said.
   In addition, Salcido was having increasing problems at the Grand
Cru winery, where he often failed to show up for his job as a
forklift operator and would call in sick when he wasn't.
   Salcido's in-laws ``bent over backwards for this guy,'' Clark
said. ``They gave him money for his apartment and still he didn't
like them. He didn't appreciate nothing.''
   Meanwhile, many residents of this picturesque region tried to
cope with the mass slayings by treating it as an isolated incident.
   In Santa Rosa, the area's biggest city with a population of
about 103,000, residents were alarmed by the killings and followed
news reports closely, but few said they felt vulnerable enough to
change plans or take unusual safety precautions while Salcido was
still at large.
   ``People aren't going to go in their houses and hide because of
it,'' said Martin Coletti, 33. ``It heightens your sensitivity to
violent crime, the worst crime, and maybe Santa Rosa is becoming
more vulnerable to that.''
   Several downtown merchants reported normal business Friday and
Saturday night. Strollers frequently pointed out that Salcido's
rage appeared to have been aimed only at family members and
acquaintances.
   ``It seems like it's a family situation,'' said Gary Lee, 49.
``I don't think he's out to hurt normal people.''
   Still, Sonoma County Sheriff's Deputy Dan Ramseier said worried
residents were calling at the rate of two or three an hour.
   ``You name it, they're worried about it. They're worried about
everything,'' he said. To reassure callers, Ramseier said he urged
residents to avoid strangers, report suspicious vehicles in the
neighborhood and keep a close eye on children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
