<SECOND>AM-Drug Arrests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0715,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than a Dozen Arrested in Drug Raid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to scale back number arrested, add details;
picks up 4th graf pvs, bgng: ``The arrests...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested more than a dozen people
during a weekend anti-drug sweep that netted the alleged leadership
of a group that controlled much of the cocaine market in the
nation's capital.
   Among those arrested were Rayful Edmond Jr., 24, and Tony Lewis,
described as being in his mid-twenties. Officials said the two led
a network that controlled up to 20 percent of the cocaine and crack
traffic in Washington.
   The Washington Post said 16 were arrested, while other reports
put the number as high as 25. Police did not release an official
figure.
   ``It was a successful operation and it is still continuing,''
assistant district police chief Max J. Krupo told the Post on
Sunday. Among those arrested were nine of Edmond's relatives, the
paper said.
   The Post quoted sources as saying the pair's alleged drug
network employed more than 150 people and has been linked to scores
of homicides. Edmond and Lewis were arrested Saturday on cocaine
distribution charges and were scheduled for arraignment on Monday.
   The arrests resulted from a two-year joint investigation
conducted by the Drug Enforcement Administration, the FBI and
district police. Officials said more information would be released
after seals on federal documents were lifted.
   The drug cartel reportedly imported as much as 440 pounds of
cocaine into the district a week. The Post quoted sources as saying
that more than a year ago Edmond's alleged drug gang was generating
income of more than $300,000 a day.
   District Mayor Marion Barry said Sunday the arrests would put
``a mini-dent'' in the local supply of drugs. However, he predicted
that in the long run, ``one of the lieutenants who know the
business will move up and keep things going.''
